At the best-guess defaults (100,000 draws), the portfolio produces a median of `{python} F["median"]` QALYs, with a 90% interval of `{python} F["p05"]` to `{python} F["p95"]` and a mean of `{python} F["mean"]`. The interval is a probabilistic-sensitivity range under the stated priors, not a confidence interval; Monte Carlo error on the median is a few hundred QALYs. The blended cost-effectiveness — dollars given over QALYs produced, at the median — is `{python} F["blended"]` per QALY. Monetized under the value-per-QALY distribution HHS recommends for regulatory analysis (central $726,000 at 3%; @aspe2026values, Table 3), the median draw-level benefit–cost ratio is `{python} F["bc"]` (90% interval `{python} F["bc_p05"]`–`{python} F["bc_p95"]`, reflecting both health-output and valuation uncertainty). @fig-dist shows the full distribution.

